<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-020-004 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 613 250</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  Nov 1991 v12 n11 p28(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>In pursuit of a single healthcare computing standard.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dunbar, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There is a significant push for unitary healthcare computingstandards, focused in large part in a new planning panel formedunder the auspices of the American National Standards Institute(ANSI).andP;  Standards are necessary to effecting open systemsinformation technologies, which will significantly reduce thecosts and and increase the accessibility of healthcare computing.andO;The ANSI planning panel headed by Clement J. McDonald, MD,includes experts from several standards organizations.andP;  The panelwants to involve all organizations developing healthcare systeminterface standards, establish a coordinating body to ensure thereis not duplication or overlap of efforts and provide a singlepoint of US response to the European Committee forStandardization's activities.andP;  Activities of other standardsorganizations are discussed, including the Computer-based PatientRecord Institute's work in establishing computer-based records asa standard, HCFA's piloting an electronic remittance program andHealth Level 7's listing service and arrangement with the Centerfor Healthcare Information Management.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Health CareIndustry AnalysisStandardizationHospital Information SystemsStandardsTrade and Professional AssociationsSystem DevelopmentGoals and ObjectivesAmerican National Standards InstituteHealth Level 7United States. Health Care Financing AdministrationComputer-based Patient Record Institute.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>